The Board of Governors of The University of Lethbridge and The University of Lethbridge Faculty Association recognize that the main purposes of the University are:
to promote the disinterested pursuit of truth and advancement of knowledge;
to promote the generation and transmission of knowledge with proper consideration given to the need for an educated citizenry;
and to give appropriate consideration to society's needs for expert advice as well as pure and applied research.

“Procedural fairness” shall mean any and all of the following:
the duty of an adjudicator to make a decision without a reasonable apprehension of bias or a conflict of interest (Prior familiarity with the facts of a case does not, by itself, constitute a reasonable apprehension of bias, nor do past friendly or unfriendly relationships);
the duty of an adjudicator to interpret and apply the Collective Agreement, including criteria of Articles 12and 14, in a reasonable and equitable manner;
A disagreement with a decision or judgement does not, in itself, constitute a misinterpretation or misapplication of the Collective Agreement, nor does it constitute an unreasonable interpretation or application of the Collective Agreement;
Differential treatment does not, in itself, constitute evidence of inequitable treatment between members when appropriate rationale can be provided;
the duty of adjudicator to ensure that adequate evidence is presented or collected to meet the standard of proof appropriate to support the decision and that such evidence is duly and appropriately considered;
the duty of an adjudicator to inform Members of their right to advice and representation from their union and to allow such advice and representation without hinderance;
that the parties to a procedure have a right to know all evidence presented and used in the decision making process;
that the parties to a procedure have an opportunity to respond to all evidence presented and used in the decision making process; AND
that the parties to a procedure have a reasonable opportunity to present their case to the adjudicator or adjudicators;
all other relevant principles of natural justice.

