In recognition of their joint responsibility for the maintenance and enforcement of the Collective Agreement, the Board agrees to provide the following support for Union activities:
the use free of charge of suitable serviced office space centrally located on the Lethbridge campus to accommodate the Association support staff, private office, and meeting space;
telephone and internet connectivity, with the telephone charges to be borne by the Association;
access to all internal services, charged at the internal user rate;
the use free of charge and without restriction of the internal campus mail delivery service for the purpose of communicating with Members;
access to meeting rooms on campus for Association business free of charge;
one (1) Annual Contractor Rover or Lot I parking permit;
use of the University payroll system at the Association's expense to pay the Association's Staff. T-4 slips shall be issued by the University;
normal access to the University's facilities, parking, identification cards, etc., for the Association's Staff, any employer contributions to be borne by the Association.

In years in which bargaining has carried over from the previous year, the additional release time provided under 5.05.1.B shall be prorated on the following basis:
bargaining ends before August 1: 0%;
bargaining ends between August 1 and October 31: 50%;
bargaining ends between November 1 and June 30: 100%.

The Association is permitted to buy single 3-credit course releases over and above those provided by the university in Article 5.05on the following basis:
Up to eight (8) single course release rates for ULFA Executive Committee or other ULFA Committee members in any year;
two (2) additional single course release rates in a bargaining year.

The University shall provide the Association with the following information in July of each year:
the names of department chairs, with the stipends they receive and the start and end dates of their appointments;
the names of all inactive Members with start and end dates of their appointments and the dues and assessments paid on their behalf to the association;
a statistical summary of all career decisions (promotions granted and not granted, merit granted, increments granted, not granted, or which would have been granted if available);
a list of all Members who received extension of probation, tenure or continuing appointment, and/or promotion in the past twelve (12) months;
a list of all Members who received conversion to a continuing or probationary appointment in the last twelve months;
a list of all sessional lecturers with right of first refusal and their Sessional Preference Score;
the number of credit courses taught by all academic staff broken down by appointment categories;

The Member’s personal file shall not include records or testimony pursuant to
the Employee Assistance Program;
any confidential mediation process.

Members have the right to be accompanied by another individual of the Member's choosing in all procedures specific in this Collective Agreement, provided that:
the individual is a Member or authorized representative of the Association;
the individual is not precluded by Article 11.06from such an accompaniment role. In the case of a dispute, resolution shall be as provided for in that Article.

Members have the right to:
maintain order and safety in the classroom, lab or other teaching or research situation and to limit the access of persons who are abusive, disruptive or who otherwise violate the rights of Members, students, or other people authorized to be present;
assistance of security personnel regarding the maintenance of such order, safety and limitations of access;
rule on the use by students of recording devices in the classroom, laboratory, or analogous learning situation, subject to reasonable accommodation of student needs and recognizing that both the Board and the Members have an obligation to accommodate students with disabilities.

Members shall have the following responsibilities as teachers:
Members shall maintain a scholarly competence and pedagogic effectiveness;
Members shall discharge their instructional responsibilities in accordance with procedures established pursuant to the provisions of the Post-Secondary Learning Act;
Members who provide instruction shall comply with procedures established pursuant to the provisions of the Post-Secondary Learning Act for reporting the grades of their students.
Subject to 35.09.6.C here, where such grades are reviewed by Department, Faculty or University committees, Members should be available for the duration of the committee's work if so required by the committee;
If 11.09.2.A.III requires the avilability of a Sessional Lecturer after the end of their contract, the Sessional Lecturer shall be compensated at the rate outlined in 35.09.6.D.
Members shall not cancel or terminate scheduled instruction except for good reason and shall give their students notice of such cancellation together with notice of any alternative instruction or rescheduling of the cancelled instruction;
Members shall be reasonably available for out of class discussions with students. Students shall have equal opportunity for such discussions;
Members shall treat students fairly in class and shall reasonably accommodate individual instructional needs;
Members shall not accept pay for tutoring a student in any subjects in which the Member is responsible for giving classroom instruction to that student, but may recommend tutors who may do so provided that no benefit, direct or indirect, accrues to the Member for that referral;
Members shall not require students to provide any services to the Member outside a formal, employer/employee relationship. Any employer/employee relationship entered into by a Member shall be reported by the Member to his/her Dean/University Librarian.
Members who becomes involved in a personal, intimate relationship with a student must disclose this personal, intimate relationship in writing to the Member’s Dean/University Librarian.
A personal, intimate relationship is one where there exists reasonable apprehension of bias between a Member and a student, and which may be perceived as conferring upon one of them an unfair advantage or subject one of them to an unfair disadvantage. Such relationships may therefore be perceived as a conflict of interest with respect to any evaluative and/or supervisory relationship between the Member and the student.
The Dean/University Librarian shall take the necessary action to ensure that any such supervision and/or evaluation is performed in a fair and reasonable manner.

Faculty Members shall have the following responsibilities in administrative and committee work:
Consistent with their primary teaching and research responsibilities, Faculty Members shall be active Members of their Departments, and Faculty Councils, and are expected, when called upon, to participate to a reasonable extent in other bodies dealing with University governance;
Administrative and Committee work can include participation in Committees and Offices of the Faculty Association;
Service duties are self-assigned under Article 13.03.2.B. Members cannot be compelled to participate in any particular Committee or Office.

Duties shall include one or more of the following:
teaching an assigned course or courses during the Fall, Spring, and/or Summer sessions, including the organization, preparation, and delivery of course material, the evaluation of students' academic progress, and individual discussions with students outside of class or laboratory hours;
supervising and examining graduate students, undergraduate honours theses, independent applied studies course, ensemble and studio students, and apprentice students in Master/Apprentice programs;
personal study and research, including study for purposes of academic self-improvement and the advancement of knowledge and understanding;
research, study, retraining, or upgrading leave on- or off-campus;
library service, in the case of Professional Librarians;
duties consistent with their position description, in the case of Instructors/Academic Assistants;
administrative and committee work at various levels - Department, Library, School, Faculty, University and Association - including academic administration, assistance at registration, and supervision of examinations;
reassignment of some or all duties to another Department, or comparable academic unit within the Faculty/Library (normally, reassignment of service or administrative duties shall presuppose reassignment of teaching or research duties); all exceptions require approval of the Vice-President (Academic), with copies to the Association; and
community service.

The Dean/University Librarian, following consultation with the appropriate Faculty/Professional Librarians Committee, shall establish and publish policies and procedures, subject to the primacy of this Collective Agreement, to determine the assignments of the Members of that Faculty/Library, provided that:
these policies and procedures shall neither be constructed nor applied at any time in such a way as to exclude a Member from consideration for the types of assignments listed in Article 13.04;
in the construction and application of these policies and procedures, an effort shall be made to ensure that the total amount of work undertaken by each Member, including the duties listed in Article 13.04, shall be reasonable and roughly equivalent in terms of the time and effort required for competent performance of that work;
these policies and procedures shall be publicly available and communicated directly with the affected Members with a copy to the Association;
the Dean/University Librarian shall consult the Member before determining that Member’s assignment; re-assignment shall similarly require consultation and Member representation by the Association be subject to policies and procedures of this Article;
the Dean/University Librarian shall give notice in writing to the Member of any assignment of duties, and that notice shall be sufficiently in advance of the assumption of those assigned duties, that the Member shall have enough time to prepare to perform those duties competently;
assignments shall fall within the Member’s area of competence;
assignments to research and study leave shall be subject to the approval of the President;
the tenure, academic salary, economic benefits and rank of a Member shall not be affected by assignment of duties under Article 13.04, unless specifically provided for otherwise in this Agreement;
the number of Faculty Members assigned to research and study leave each year shall accord with past practice.

The principal responsibility of Instructors is to provide instruction within the Department/Faculty/Library through laboratory, clinical, or other teaching assignments and related duties. In every case, the Member must be appropriately qualified to teach the courses in question.
Instructor I: Full responsibility for teaching laboratory, fine arts studio performance, physical activity or practicum courses is part of the Member's regular assigned duties. Full responsibility for teaching a course may be assigned with appropriate supervision and with the express permission of the Dean/University Librarian;
Instructor II: Full responsibility for teaching one or more courses may be part of a Member's regular assigned duties;
Instructor III: Full responsibility for teaching courses may constitute all or part of a Member’s regular assigned duties.

Assessments for salary increments and for appointment to a continuing position shall be based upon:
effectiveness and competence with which assigned duties are carried out;
the effectiveness with which the other rights and responsibilities listed in Articles 15.02.4, where applicable, are carried out.

Faculty members may be offered one of the following types of appointment:
a term appointment;
a probationary appointment;
a term appointment with conversion; or
an appointment with tenure.

Except for such provision as specified in Article 18.02.4, a term appointment shall not be made except under one or more of the following conditions:
that the appointment is a replacement for a Faculty Member on leave or on another assignment of duties;
that the appointment is of someone unqualified for continuing appointment because a person with the required qualifications is not available at the time;
that the duties connected with the appointment are for a limited period and are expected to be no longer required after the specified date;
that the appointment is caused by the sudden unforeseen departure of a Faculty Member;
that the appointment is to afford flexibility in program development for a specified period as determined by the Vice-President (Academic) and communicated to the Association in writing;
that the appointment has been made by the Dean in response to a failed search (see Article ).

A term appointment may contain provisions for conversion into a probationary appointment. There shall be two bases for such possibility of conversion:
the term appointment is made in an area reliant on contingent funding that may become permanent (in this case, the letter of appointment shall specify the conditions under which conversion may occur, such as the availability of continuing funding for the position, attainment of academic credentials, and satisfactory performance of the duties for which the appointment was made);
upon attainment of specific academic credential(s).

The normal appointment year shall be from July 1 to the following June 30. However it shall be possible for an appointment to be made effective at other times of the year:
For an appointment taking effect after July 1 but no later than September 1 of a year, the first appointment year shall end on the following June 30;
For an appointment that becomes effective after September 1, the first appointment year shall end a year from the immediately following June 30.

The Committee's procedures shall be as follows:
The Committee Chair shall recommend to the STP Committee performance ratings (relative to weightings) and the resultant performance score. Before such a recommendation the Chair shall:
invite the Faculty Member/Professional Librarian to supply a rationale and whatever material, evidence, and information he/she presented to the Dean/University Librarian to justify his/her preferred performance ratings (relative to the weightings of the Dean/University Librarian);
request from the Dean/University Librarian the Professional Activities Report, any supporting documentation provided by the Faculty Member/Professional Librarian, and the Department Chair’s assessment (where applicable) which were the basis for the Dean/University Librarian’s performance rating;
invite the Dean/University Librarian to justify his/her performance rating, a copy of which justification shall be provided to the Faculty Member/Professional Librarian;
inform the Faculty Member/Professional Librarian of the right to Association representaiton and the right to appear before the STP Committee, giving as much notice as possible but not fewer than five (5) working days’ notice. Normally new documentation shall not be presented at this meeting.
The Chair shall convene the STP Committee and shall place before it:
The items specified in Article 21.05.9.B;
The motion, which shall be The Dean’s/University Librarian's recommendation regarding performance rating be accepted.
If that motion fails, another motion shall be made regarding the appropriate performance rating to be recommended to the President.
After examining the evidence before the committee, the STP Committee may request the Chair to attempt to gather additional evidence within reasonable limits. The Faculty Member/Professional Librarian will be provided with a fair summary of any new documentation admitted and will have five (5) working days to respond to it prior to the Committee considering the new documentation.
A letter from the Chair of the STP Committee shall be transmitted to the Dean/University Librarian, with a copy to the Faculty Member/Professional Librarian and the Association, informing the Dean/University Librarian and the Faculty Member/Professional Librarian of the Committee's recommendation and the reasons therefor.
All materials used in the Hearing shall be deemed to be part of the Faculty Member/Professional Librarian's Personal File, subject to the provisions of Article 9.

To be eligible to have a performance evaluation every two (2) years a Member shall meet the following criteria:
is tenured or holds a continuing appointment, as appropriate;
has received at least a normal career progress increment for each of the last 3 years;
has not received a report in writing of unsatisfactory performance of academic duties during the last 3 years; and
has not been disciplined under Article 25in the last three (3) years.

The following matters shall not be subject to grievance:
the outcome of appeals respecting the promotion, extension of probation, tenure or salary of a Member;
the outcome of a specific process provided by this Collective Agreement that is binding on both parties;
a request for amendment of this Collective Agreement;
a matter not covered by the Collective Agreement or applicable legislation.

Any violation of the University’s standards of performance or rules of conduct is subject to appropriate supervisory action, shall normally be initiated by the Member’s Dean/University Librarian and may include such measures as:
verbal discussion;
a letter of guidance, a letter of reprimand;
or major discipline.

The Vice-President (Academic) shall within fifteen (15) working days following receipt of the complaint make one of the following decisions, and shall so advise the complainant Dean/University Librarian, the Member, and the Association:
to authorize an investigation of the complaint;
to dismiss the complaint;
to require the complainant Dean/University Librarian and/or the Member to follow the alternative measures below.

A state of financial emergency is defined as a situation in which the University faces a substantial and potentially chronic accounting deficit which
is projected to extend for more than two (2) years;
threatens to turn into a deficit in cash flow;
threatens the continued functioning of the University as a whole;
cannot be alleviated without layoffs from more than one employee group on campus in order to reduce the University’s budgetary allocation to salaries and benefits; and
the proposed layoffs include an equal or larger proportion of the Senior Administration to that proposed for the Academic Staff.

A program may be declared redundant for one or more of the following reasons:
changing University priorities or restructuring of the University’s academic programs as a consequence of a decision by the Board, following a recommendation by GFC that the University make major changes in its priorities;
low student enrolment: when recent history and reasonable projections into the future indicate that the level of enrolment, in proportion to the resources committed to that program, will continue for more than four (4) years significantly below the average of the relevant faculty;
a material loss of funding given to the University for the support of the specific program;
other external factors which specifically affect enrolment in the particular program and over which the University has no control, such as changes in the requirements for certification in various professions.

The Redundancy Committee shall be composed as follows:
a chair appointed by GFC;
two (2) other members and one (1) alternate appointed by the GFC;
one (1) member appointed by the Vice-President (Academic);
the Dean of the faculty involved; and,
two (2) members and one (1) alternate appointed by the Association;
two (2) members and one (1) alternate, with voice but not vote, appointed by the Board.

The Redundancy Committee shall establish its own procedures, except that:
its hearings shall be open to the University community;
its quorum shall be four (4) voting members;
reasonable effort shall be made to schedule meetings to allow attendance by the majority of members, both voting and non-voting.

Concurrent with any offer under Article 26.05.1, the Board shall make reasonable efforts to offer to each Faculty Member/Professional Librarian in a redundant program one or more of the following, as deemed appropriate by the Board:
reassignment according to Article 26.06;
retraining according to Articles 13.04or 26.07;
any other alternative which may be implemented with the mutual consent of the Board and the Faculty Member/Professional Librarian.

In the cases referred to in Article 29.04.3, the Board will normally transfer its ownership rights on such a work to the author (or group of authors) provided:
Any author who seeks to secure the ownership of copyright applies to the President for such a transfer on an Assignment of Copyright Form;
The applicant has obtained and provided to the President prior written agreement of all co-authors of the work;

The University will transfer by written agreement with copies to the Association its ownership right to the work under the following conditions:
that the University shall have unhampered use of the material for its internal instructional and research activities;
that the author named in the agreement shall return to the University fifty percent (50%) of the royalty the author may receive from use of the copyright;
that the author, if so requested by the University, shall display the University’s name on the work if it is published, publicly displayed, performed, or exhibited.

Salary schedules shall be as set forth in Schedule A, and shall include the following:
A minimum stipend, exclusive of holiday pay and other statutory benefits, for Sessional Lecturers;
A salary schedule for Instructors/Academic Assistants, specifying minimum and maximum salaries for each class;
A salary schedule for Faculty Members/Professional Librarians, specifying the minimum salary for each rank.

A separate merit pool fund shall be established for each Faculty and for the Library as follows:
For each Faculty Member/Professional Librarian, the per-Member merit pool contribution as specified in Schedule shall be part of the fund;
The merit pool shall be distributed among Faculty Members/Professional Librarians in the form of a merit award on June 30 of each year. The Association shall be informed of the amount of merit and value of the merit pool for each faculty each year.

To the degree permitted by relevant legislation, this certificant shall
Specify that the Member requires medical leave;
Provide an estimate of the duration of the member's absence.

Upon receipt of the report of the wellness officer and, if provided, the external evaluation described in Article AE, the Provost shall take appropriate to resolve the case, including, but not restricted to the following:
placing a member on medical leave;
requiring the member to continue on medical leave;
requiring the member to return to regular responsibilities;
requiring the member to return to reduced or adapted resposibilities;
requiring the member to apply for disability benefits;
requiring the member to participate in an appropriate treatment programme;
offering to negotiation a voluntary retirement or resignation under Article 16.08.

A member is entitled to up to eight (8) weeks of paid domestic and sexual violence leave in each academic year, without reduction in salary or benefits. Paid domestic violence leave may be extended in exceptional circumstances. “Domestic Violence” means:
any intentional or reckless action that causes injury or property damage while intimidating or harming a person;
any act that intimidates a person by creating a reasonable fear for property damage or personal injury;
psychological, verbal or emotional abuse;
forced confinement;
sexual contact without a person’s explicit and ongoing consent including but not limited to: sexual assault, sexual harassment, stalking, indecent exposure, voyeurism, sexual exploitation and sexual solicitation, and may include acts that occur online in or outside of the context of ongoing domestic or intimate partner relationships; and
economic abuse or control including but not limited to: diminishing a person and/or their dependents’ access to economic and household resources, sabotaging childcare and/or transportation; or
a threat or attempt to do an act described above.

